            ['title' => 'Surah Al-Duha: Allah Has Not Forgotten You', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study Surah Al-Duha (93) — revealed as a comfort to the Prophet ﷺ during a time of trial — and apply its message of divine care to personal moments of difficulty.', 'instructions' => '1. Context: the Prophet ﷺ experienced a pause in revelation and felt abandoned — this surah was the answer.\n2. Read and translate Surah Al-Duha.\n3. Three promises of Allah: the future will be better, He has not forgotten you, He will give you until you are pleased.\n4. Write about a time you felt forgotten or low — what would these three promises say to you?', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, notebook, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify Al-Duha\'s three promises and apply their comfort to a personal experience', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Surah Al-Inshirah: Ease After Hardship', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Memorise and study Surah Al-Inshirah (94) — the companion to Al-Duha — embracing the repeated promise "verily with hardship comes ease."', 'instructions' => '1. Memorise Surah Al-Inshirah (8 short verses).\n2. The key promise is stated twice — scholars say: "One hardship cannot overpower two eases."\n3. What does "expansion of the chest" mean spiritually? (Clarity, peace, removal of burdens)\n4. Write 3 hardships you are facing and 3 "eases" Allah has already placed alongside them.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, notebook, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Memorise Al-Inshirah and apply its promise of ease to personal hardships', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Seven Long Surahs (As-Sab\' al-Tiwal)', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 10, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Overview and briefly study the 7 long surahs of the Quran, understanding the major legal, narrative, and theological content of each.', 'instructions' => '1. Name the 7 long surahs: Al-Baqarah, Al-Imran, An-Nisa, Al-Ma\'idah, Al-An\'am, Al-A\'raf, and (debated: At-Tawbah or Al-Anfal).\n2. For each: 2 key themes and 1 notable story or ruling.\n3. Which contains the most legal rulings? (Al-Baqarah and Al-Ma\'idah)\n4. Set a goal to read 1 long surah in the next month.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, reference list, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Name the 7 long surahs and identify 2 key themes for each', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Quran Review: What I Know and Where I\'m Going', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'A comprehensive self-assessment of the Quran module — reviewing memorisation, understanding, and tajweed progress, and creating a forward-looking personal Quran development plan.', 'instructions' => '1. Recite memorised surahs in one sitting.\n2. List: 5 things you now know about the Quran that you didn\'t before.\n3. List: 3 tajweed improvements you have made.\n4. Write your Quran 6-month plan: surahs to memorise, rules to master, knowledge to gain.\n5. Make du\'a for consistency and sincerity in your Quran journey.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, journal, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Produce a comprehensive Quran self-assessment and a 6-month development plan', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Loving the Quran: The Companion Who Intercedes', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Develop a heart relationship with the Quran — understanding the hadith about intercession, the reward for every letter, and the honour of the huffaz — building lifelong Quran love.', 'instructions' => '1. Hadith: "The Quran will come as an intercessor for its companion on the Day of Resurrection." (Muslim)\n2. Hadith: "Whoever recites a letter of the Quran will have a good deed, and each good deed is multiplied by 10." (Tirmidhi)\n3. Discuss: the word "companion" suggests a relationship — how do you build a relationship with the Quran?\n4. Write a love letter to the Quran.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, notebook, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Articulate the spiritual relationship between a Muslim and the Quran using hadith evidence', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],

            // Islamic Studies 1-20
            ['title' => 'The Five Pillars of Islam', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the 5 pillars of Islam — Shahadah, Salah, Zakat, Sawm, Hajj — understanding each one\'s meaning, conditions, and place in a Muslim\'s life.', 'instructions' => '1. List and name all 5 pillars.\n2. For each: what is it, who must perform it, when, and why?\n3. Build a visual: 5 pillars diagram or model.\n4. Which pillar do you think is hardest? Which is most important? Discuss.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, coloured markers, plain paper', 'learning_objectives' => 'Name and explain each of the 5 pillars of Islam with conditions and purpose', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Six Pillars of Iman (Faith)', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the 6 pillars of Iman: belief in Allah, angels, books, messengers, the Last Day, and divine decree — building a foundational understanding of Islamic belief.', 'instructions' => '1. Recite the hadith of Jibril on iman.\n2. For each pillar: full explanation and one Quranic or hadith evidence.\n3. Focus on Qadar (divine decree): how does belief in qadar affect how a Muslim faces hardship?\n4. Write a personal iman declaration about the pillar that means most to you.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain all 6 pillars of iman with evidence and reflect on how each shapes daily life', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Who is Allah? Tawheed for School Children', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand tawheed — the pure monotheism of Islam — through the lens of Allah\'s uniqueness in His Being, Names, and Attributes, and His right to be worshipped alone.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: tawheed = oneness. There is only one Allah — unlike anything in creation.\n2. Three categories: Tawheed ar-Rububiyyah (Lord), al-Uluhiyyah (worship), al-Asma wa\'s-Sifat (names and attributes).\n3. Why is shirk (associating partners) the greatest sin?\n4. Write a tawheed poem: what makes Allah unique.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the 3 categories of tawheed and describe why shirk is the gravest sin', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Angels: Creation and Roles', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn about the angels in Islam — created from light, without desires, always obedient — and the specific roles of 7 major angels.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: angels created from light, no free will to sin.\n2. Name and explain 7 angels: Jibril, Mika\'il, Israfil, Azra\'il, Munkar and Nakir, Ridwan, Malik.\n3. The two angels recording deeds — how does knowing this change your behaviour?\n4. Write: which angel\'s role do you find most comforting and why?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Name 7 angels, describe each role, and reflect on how this belief affects behaviour', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Salah: The Gift of Prayer', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the full salah — conditions, pillars, times, number of rak\'ahs, and the spiritual meaning behind each movement — with special focus on the Night Journey when it was gifted.', 'instructions' => '1. Salah was gifted on the Night Journey (Isra wal Mi\'raj) — what makes it special?\n2. The 5 prayers: names, times, number of rak\'ahs.\n3. Conditions: taharah, qiblah, time, covering.\n4. Pillars of salah: niyyah, takbeer, recitation, ruku, sujood, tashahhud, tasleem.\n5. Role-play: demonstrate a complete 2-rak\'ah prayer correctly.', 'materials_needed' => 'Prayer mat, Quran, reference guide', 'learning_objectives' => 'Demonstrate a complete 2-rak\'ah prayer correctly with all pillars', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Wudu and Taharah: Purity in Islam', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the steps and conditions of wudu, ghusl, and the concept of najaasah — understanding that inner and outer purity are both essential in Islam.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: taharah covers both outer (physical) and inner (spiritual) purity.\n2. Steps of wudu in correct order: intention, Bismillah, hands, mouth, nose, face, right arm, left arm, head, ears, right foot, left foot.\n3. What breaks wudu?\n4. Demonstrate full wudu and check each step.\n5. Discuss: why does salah require wudu — what does physical preparation say about spiritual preparation?', 'materials_needed' => 'Water, towel', 'learning_objectives' => 'Perform wudu correctly in order and explain what invalidates it', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Ramadan: The Month of the Quran', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the virtues, rulings, and spiritual dimensions of Ramadan — why it is the best month, the purpose of fasting, the last 10 nights, and Laylat al-Qadr.', 'instructions' => '1. Why is Ramadan so special? (Revelation of Quran, gates of Jannah open, Shaytan chained)\n2. Purpose of fasting: taqwa — not just hunger and thirst.\n3. Who must fast? Exceptions.\n4. The last 10 nights: Laylat al-Qadr — "better than 1000 months."\n5. Design a Ramadan goals chart.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, Ramadan goal chart template', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the purpose of Ramadan, the conditions of fasting, and the significance of Laylat al-Qadr', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Zakat and Sadaqah: Purifying Wealth', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the difference between zakat (obligatory) and sadaqah (voluntary), who must pay, how much (nisab and 2.5%), and to whom it is given.', 'instructions' => '1. Define zakat: purification of wealth. Sadaqah: voluntary giving.\n2. Nisab threshold: approximately 87.5g of gold or 612.5g of silver in current value.\n3. Rate: 2.5% of qualifying wealth held for 1 lunar year.\n4. 8 categories of zakat recipients (9:60).\n5. Calculate: if someone has £10,000 savings above nisab, how much zakat do they owe?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, calculator, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain zakat conditions, nisab, and calculate a simple zakat amount', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Hajj: The Journey of a Lifetime', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the rituals of Hajj — ihram, tawaf, sa\'i, Arafah, Muzdalifah, Mina, and stoning — understanding the story of Ibrahim (AS) behind each one.', 'instructions' => '1. Map the Hajj journey on a diagram of Makkah and surrounding areas.\n2. For each ritual: what is it, when is it done, and which story of Ibrahim (AS) does it commemorate?\n3. Discuss: why do millions gather in the same clothes — what does this symbolise?\n4. Have you (or your family) performed Hajj? If not, make du\'a that you will.', 'materials_needed' => 'Hajj ritual map, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the rituals of Hajj and explain the Ibrahimic connection of each', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Day of Judgement: What the Quran Describes', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn what the Quran and Sunnah describe about the Day of Judgement — the resurrection, the gathering, the scales, the bridge, intercession — building belief in the afterlife.', 'instructions' => '1. Sequence: the blowing of the Soor (trumpet), resurrection, gathering, questioning, books of deeds, scales (Mizan), the bridge (Sirat).\n2. For each: one Quranic or hadith reference.\n3. The intercession of the Prophet ﷺ (Shafa\'ah al-Uzma).\n4. Reflect: how does belief in the Day of Judgement change your daily choices?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, reference', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the events of the Day of Judgement with one reference per event', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Life of the Prophet ﷺ : Birth to Prophethood', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the early life of the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ — his birth, fatherless upbringing, Halimah, the opening of the chest, childhood in Makkah, and the revelation at Cave Hira.', 'instructions' => '1. Timeline: birth (Year of the Elephant), father\'s death before birth, mother Aminah, grandfather Abd al-Muttalib, wet-nurse Halimah, mother Aminah dies aged 6, with grandfather then Abu Talib.\n2. Character before prophethood: Al-Amin — the trustworthy.\n3. The night of revelation: Cave Hira, Jibril, "Iqra."\n4. Write: what prepared the Prophet ﷺ for prophethood throughout his early life?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Narrate the major events of the Prophet\'s early life up to the first revelation', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Makkan Period: Trials and Steadfastness', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the 13 years of the Makkan period — the first believers, the persecution, Bilal and others, the boycott, the Year of Grief, and the Isra wal Mi\'raj.', 'instructions' => '1. First believers: Khadijah, Ali, Zayd, Abu Bakr.\n2. The persecution: Bilal, Ammar ibn Yasir, Sumayyah (first martyr).\n3. The Boycott: 3 years of starvation and isolation.\n4. The Year of Grief: deaths of Khadijah and Abu Talib.\n5. The Isra wal Mi\'raj: consolation and the gift of prayer.\n6. What does this period teach about sabr?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, timeline template', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the key events and figures of the Makkan period and reflcet on its lessons', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Madinan Period: Building a Community', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the 10 Madinan years — the Hijrah, the Constitution of Madinah, bond of brotherhood, the battles of Badr and Uhud, the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, and the Conquest of Makkah.', 'instructions' => '1. Timeline: Hijrah, Constitution of Madinah, brotherhood of Ansar and Muhajirun, Badr, Uhud, Ahzab, Hudaybiyyah, Conquest of Makkah.\n2. Key lessons from each event.\n3. Conquest of Makkah: general pardon — what does this teach about Islamic justice and mercy?\n4. Write: how did the Prophet ﷺ transform a society in 10 years?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the key events of the Madinan period and identify their central lessons', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Ethics: Halal and Haram Explained', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the Islamic framework of halal and haram — why things are permitted or forbidden, the principle that everything is halal unless prohibited, and the 5 objectives of Islamic law (maqasid).', 'instructions' => '1. Principle: "the default is permissibility" — only specific things are haram.\n2. Introduce maqasid ash-shari\'ah: protection of religion, life, mind, lineage, wealth.\n3. Examples: why is alcohol haram? (harms mind and family) Why is gambling haram? (harms wealth and justice)\n4. Case study: apply the maqasid framework to a modern ethical question.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the halal/haram framework using the 5 maqasid as a reasoning tool', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Eid al-Fitr and Eid al-Adha: Celebrations of Worship', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the two Islamic Eids — their spiritual meaning, rituals, and the social bond they create — distinguishing them from cultural celebrations.', 'instructions' => '1. Eid al-Fitr: after Ramadan, Eid prayer, Zakat al-Fitr (why it comes before the prayer).\n2. Eid al-Adha: after Hajj, the story of Ibrahim\'s sacrifice, the meaning of the udhiyah (sacrifice).\n3. Both Eids: community prayer, charitable giving, visiting family.\n4. Discuss: how are Islamic celebrations different in spirit from secular ones?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the spiritual meaning and rituals of both Eids', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Jannah: The Garden of Paradise', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the Quranic and hadith descriptions of Jannah — its gates, levels, rivers, trees, and the greatest gift of all: seeing Allah — building genuine longing for it.', 'instructions' => '1. Hadith: "In Jannah there is what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has imagined."\n2. The 8 gates of Jannah and what each is for.\n3. Levels of Jannah: Firdaws is the highest.\n4. Greatest joy: seeing Allah\'s face — discuss why this is the ultimate reward.\n5. Write 5 deeds that lead to Jannah.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Describe the key features of Jannah from Quran and Hadith and identify 5 deeds that lead to it', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Tawbah: Returning to Allah', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the conditions of sincere tawbah (repentance) in Islam: remorse, stopping the sin, intention not to return, and making right any wrongs done to others.', 'instructions' => '1. Hadith: "All of the children of Adam are sinners, and the best of sinners are those who repent." (Tirmidhi)\n2. 4 conditions: regret, stop, intend not to return, (if the right of a person) make it right.\n3. How does Islam\'s concept of tawbah differ from having to go through an intermediary (e.g., a priest)?\n4. Make silent personal tawbah.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply the 4 conditions of tawbah and reflect on its direct nature in Islam', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic History: The Rightly Guided Caliphs', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the Khulafa Rashidun — Abu Bakr, Umar, Uthman, Ali (RA) — their selection, key decisions, and the conditions of their rule.', 'instructions' => '1. Timeline: Abu Bakr (2 years): Ridda wars, Quran compilation. Umar (10 years): vast expansion, justice. Uthman (12 years): Quran copying, assassination. Ali (5 years): civil strife, martyrdom.\n2. For each: 2 achievements and 2 challenges.\n3. The hadith: "Hold fast to my Sunnah and the Sunnah of the Rightly-Guided Caliphs after me."\n4. What can we learn from how they governed?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, timeline template', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the 4 caliphs with key achievements and identify lessons for Islamic governance', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],


            // Islamic Studies 21-45
            ['title' => 'Fiqh of Salah: Correcting Common Mistakes', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Identify and correct 10 common mistakes children make in salah — from posture in ruku and sujood to the stillness (tuma\'ninah) required in every position.', 'instructions' => '1. List 10 common prayer mistakes: rushing, not straightening back in ruku, not resting between sujood, not saying tashahhud slowly, etc.\n2. For each: what is the correct way?\n3. Demonstrate correct ruku and sujood position.\n4. Tuma\'ninah: the Prophet ﷺ said "Then bow until you are STILL in ruku." — practise stillness.\n5. Perform a 2-rak\'ah prayer focusing on correcting all 10.', 'materials_needed' => 'Prayer mat', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify and correct 10 common salah errors in a demonstrated prayer', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Dua: The Weapon of the Believer', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the etiquette of making dua, the best times for dua, and memorise 10 important everyday duas from the Sunnah.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: dua is direct communication with Allah — no intermediary needed.\n2. Best times: last third of night, between adhan and iqamah, on Fridays, in sujood, when it rains, while fasting.\n3. Etiquette: face qiblah, raise hands, begin with praise and salawat, be specific, have certainty.\n4. Learn 10 Arabic duas: morning, evening, before eating, leaving home, entering home, before sleep, when distressed, for parents, dua of Yunus, dua for guidance.', 'materials_needed' => 'Dua card set, Quran reference', 'learning_objectives' => 'Memorise 10 Sunnah duas and identify the best times to make dua', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Seerat al-Nabi ﷺ : His Manners and Character', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study 10 character traits of the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ with authentic hadith, building admiration and desire to follow his example in daily life.', 'instructions' => '1. "Indeed, you are of a great moral character." (Quran 68:4)\n2. Study 10 traits with hadith: gentleness with Aisha, generosity, patience with the Taif trip, smiling at companions, caring for animals, cleanliness, helping at home.\n3. For each: one hadith, one modern-life application.\n4. Write: which trait do you most want to embody and why?', 'materials_needed' => 'Hadith reference, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Describe 10 prophetic character traits with hadith and identify personal applications', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Finance Basics: Riba and Halal Earning', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand why riba (interest) is forbidden in Islam, what makes income halal, and basic alternatives to conventional banking — building Islamic financial literacy.', 'instructions' => '1. Define riba and why it is haram: exploitation, inequality, harm to the poor.\n2. Quranic warning: "Allah has permitted trade and forbidden riba." (2:275)\n3. What makes income halal? (honest work, no deception, no harm)\n4. Islamic alternatives: murabaha, musharakah, Takaful insurance.\n5. Apply: is a savings account with interest halal or haram? What should you do with accidentally received interest?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the prohibition of riba and identify characteristics of halal income', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic View on Health and Medicine', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the Islamic obligation to seek medicine, the concept of tib al-nabawi (prophetic medicine), and the balance between trusting Allah and taking practical means for health.', 'instructions' => '1. Hadith: "There is a cure for every disease." (Muslim)\n2. Seeking medicine is not contrary to tawakkul — explain why (tawakkul = trust + action).\n3. Prophetic medicine: honey, black seed.\n4. Forbidden in medicine: haram substances unless no permissible alternative (rule of necessity).\n5. Discuss: what Islamic guidance applies if a medicine contains a small amount of alcohol?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the Islamic framework for seeking medical treatment and identify prophetic remedies', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Sahabah: Great Companions of the Prophet ﷺ', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study 10 notable Companions — Abu Bakr, Umar, Uthman, Ali, Bilal, Khadijah, Aisha, Fatimah, Khalid ibn al-Walid, and Ibn Mas\'ud — and the lesson each teaches.', 'instructions' => '1. For each Sahabi: brief biography, key contribution to Islam, quality to emulate.\n2. Abu Bakr: loyalty. Umar: justice. Bilal: perseverance against oppression. Aisha: scholarship. Fatimah: devotion.\n3. Discussion: why does Islam preserve so many companion stories? (Model behaviour for every century)\n4. Which Sahabi inspires you most and why?', 'materials_needed' => 'Reference book or notes, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Describe 10 Companions and identify one quality from each to personally emulate', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Hajj and Umrah: Journey to the House of Allah', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Compare Hajj and Umrah — shared rituals, what is unique to each, and the spiritual transformation that millions experience at the Ka\'bah every year.', 'instructions' => '1. Compare Hajj and Umrah: what rituals are shared (tawaf, sa\'i) and what is unique to Hajj (Arafah, Muzdalifah, stoning)?\n2. Virtual Hajj: trace the journey on a map.\n3. Why does Hajj require specific days? What does Arafah represent?\n4. Discuss: one million people in ihram — what does equality look like in Islam?', 'materials_needed' => 'Hajj map, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Compare the rituals of Hajj and Umrah and explain the significance of ibadah at each site', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Golden Age: Scholars Who Changed the World', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the Islamic Golden Age (8th–13th C) — the contributions of Muslim scholars to mathematics, astronomy, medicine, and philosophy — and the Islamic value of seeking knowledge.', 'instructions' => '1. Introduce: while Europe was in the dark ages, Muslim scholars preserved and advanced knowledge.\n2. Study 5 scholars: Ibn Sina (medicine), Al-Khwarizmi (algebra), Al-Biruni (earth sciences), Ibn al-Haytham (optics), Al-Razi (chemistry).\n3. For each: contribution and one specific discovery still in use today.\n4. What drove this tradition? The Islamic command to seek knowledge.', 'materials_needed' => 'Reference materials, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify 5 Golden Age scholars and describe one lasting contribution each', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Rights of Others in Islam', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the rights Islam gives to parents, neighbours, guests, travellers, non-Muslims in an Islamic state, and the poor — building a framework of obligations toward others.', 'instructions' => '1. For each group: parents, spouse, children, neighbours, guests, poor, traveller — 2 specific rights from Hadith.\n2. Hadith: "The one who sleeps full while his neighbour goes hungry is not from us." — what does this demand of us?\n3. Rights of non-Muslims in an Islamic community.\n4. Identify 3 people in your life and list your specific obligations toward them.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'List the rights of 5 categories of people from Hadith and apply them personally', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Understanding Mainstream vs Deviant Beliefs', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 10, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the Ahl al-Sunnah wal-Jama\'ah (mainstream Islam) and the criteria for identifying beliefs that contradict clear Quranic and hadith guidance — taught in a balanced, non-confrontational way.', 'instructions' => '1. Define Ahl al-Sunnah: following the Quran, Sunnah, and the consensus of the companions.\n2. The 73 groups hadith — what was the Prophet ﷺ warning against?\n3. Criteria for evaluating claims: is it in the Quran? Is it in authenticated Hadith? Is it agreed upon by the early Muslims?\n4. When encountering an unusual Islamic claim — what questions should you ask?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply the Ahl al-Sunnah criteria to evaluate Islamic claims using Quran and Hadith evidence', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Death and the Afterlife: Preparing for Eternity', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the Islamic stages of the afterlife — Barzakh (the intermediate state), the Day of Judgement, Jannah, and Jahannam — and how this belief gives life meaning and purpose.', 'instructions' => '1. Stages: death → Barzakh (grave) → Day of Judgement → Jannah or Jahannam.\n2. Barzakh: for believers, a blessing; for wrongdoers, a type of reckoning begins.\n3. Munkar and Nakir: the 3 questions asked in the grave.\n4. Reflect: knowing this is coming — what do you want your "book of deeds" to look like?\n5. Write 5 deeds you will focus on.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Sequence the Islamic afterlife stages and reflect on implications for current choices', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Importance of Seeking Knowledge in Islam', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the Islamic obligation and honour of seeking knowledge — the first word revealed was Iqra, and the status of scholars in Islam — inspiring a lifelong love of learning.', 'instructions' => '1. First word revealed: "Read!" — what does this tell us about Islam\'s priorities?\n2. Hadith: "Seeking knowledge is an obligation upon every Muslim." (Ibn Majah)\n3. The status of scholars: "The scholars are the heirs of the prophets."\n4. What kinds of knowledge? Fard Ayn (personal religious duty) vs Fard Kifayah (collective duty in different fields).\n5. Write your personal learning manifesto.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the Islamic obligation of seeking knowledge and distinguish fard ayn from fard kifayah', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Masjid: The House of Allah', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the history and functions of the masjid — not just a place of prayer but a community centre, school, and refuge — from the Prophet\'s first masjid in Madinah.', 'instructions' => '1. History: the Prophet\'s first act upon arriving in Madinah was to build the masjid.\n2. Functions: prayer, community meetings, education, refuge, place of \'ikaf (retreat).\n3. The 7 categories who will be under Allah\'s shade — one is "a man whose heart is attached to the masjid."\n4. How can you be more connected to your local masjid?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the functions of the masjid and identify ways to build a masjid connection', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Art, Music, and Entertainment', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the Islamic perspective on art, entertainment, and music — what is permitted (nasheeds, Quran recitation, beneficial art), what is debated, and what is clearly prohibited.', 'instructions' => '1. What is clearly permitted: beneficial speech, poetry, nasheeds, sport.\n2. Clearly prohibited: music with vulgarity, content leading to haram, wasting time in negligence.\n3. The area of scholarly debate: musical instruments — summarise the positions without dismissing either.\n4. Principle: the purpose and effect matter, not just the form.\n5. Design your own halal entertainment plan for a typical week.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply Islamic criteria to evaluate entertainment choices using the principle of purpose and effect', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Role of Women in Islam: Honour and Contribution', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the elevated status of women in Islam — Prophet ﷺ\'s honour of women, female scholars, their role in early Islam (Aisha, Khadijah, Fatimah) — correcting misconceptions.', 'instructions' => '1. Read the hadith on mothers: "Paradise is under the feet of mothers."\n2. Study 5 female Companions and their contributions: Khadijah (first believer, support), Aisha (hadith scholar), Fatimah (devotion), Asma (migration helper), Umm Sulaym (courage).\n3. The Prophet ﷺ\'s treatment of women: "The best of you is the best to his family."\n4. Discuss: how does Islam honour women vs. how they are sometimes portrayed?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, reference materials', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify 5 female Companions and their contributions and explain Islamic teachings on women\'s honour', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Making the Right Choice: Islamic Decision-Making', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the Islamic decision-making model: consult the Quran, Hadith, and scholars; make Istikhara; consult trusted people; then act with tawakkul.', 'instructions' => '1. Islamic decision-making: Quran first → Hadith → scholarly opinion → shura (consultation) → Istikhara + action.\n2. What is Istikhara? Teach the dua and explain: it is asking for guidance, not a sign.\n3. Role-play: should I join this activity, take this course? Apply the decision model.\n4. Write: a decision you are facing — walk through the Islamic process.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply the Islamic decision-making process to a personal dilemma using all 4 steps', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Shirk Awareness: Protecting Tawheed', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand the different levels of shirk (major and minor) and how to protect tawheed in everyday life, from pure worship to guarding against riya (showing off).', 'instructions' => '1. Major shirk: worshipping others alongside Allah.\n2. Minor shirk: riya (showing off in worship).\n3. Hidden shirk: doing good deeds for approval of people.\n4. Protective dua: say before each worship: "I seek Your forgiveness for all known and unknown shirk."\n5. How does regular istighfar protect against minor shirk?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Distinguish major from minor shirk and apply protective practices to safeguard tawheed', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Contemporary Muslim Challenges and Responses', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 10, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Navigate 5 contemporary challenges facing Muslim youth — identity, online fitna, pressure to abandon values, misinformation about Islam, and Islamophobia — with Islamic responses.', 'instructions' => '1. Discuss each challenge honestly: what does a young Muslim face?\n2. Islamic response framework: strong aqeedah, Islamic knowledge, righteous company, connection to Allah.\n3. Islamophobia: respond with knowledge, confidence, and good character. "The best of you is the best in character." (Bukhari)\n4. Write: which challenge feels most relevant to you? What is your personal response strategy?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify 5 contemporary challenges and formulate an Islamic response framework for each', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Fiqh of Fasting: Rules and Spiritual Goals', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the fiqh rulings of fasting — what invalidates the fast, the etiquette of suhoor and iftar, voluntary fasting — and reconnect to the spiritual goals: taqwa, gratitude, empathy.', 'instructions' => '1. What breaks the fast: eating, drinking, intentional vomiting. (Medical injections: scholarly difference).\n2. What does NOT break the fast: forgetting, using miswak.\n3. Suhoor: "Eat suhoor, for in it there is blessing."\n4. Iftar etiquette: break with dates and water, iftar dua.\n5. Voluntary fasts: Mondays and Thursdays, 6 days of Shawwal, Day of Arafah.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply fasting fiqh by correctly categorising activities as fast-breaking or permitted', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Studies Review: What I Know and Believe', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 35, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'A comprehensive milestone review of Islamic Studies learning — testing aqeedah, fiqh, seerah, and akhlaq knowledge through a structured self-assessment quiz.', 'instructions' => '1. Review sections: Aqeedah (6 pillars, 5 pillars, tawheed), Fiqh (wudu, salah, fasting, zakat, hajj), Seerah (Prophet\'s life, companions, caliphs), Akhlaq (character traits, Islamic ethics).\n2. Self-quiz: 5 questions per section.\n3. Mark: which areas are strong? Which need review?\n4. Make a plan: 2 topics to study more deeply.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quiz template, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Complete a cross-topic Islamic Studies self-assessment and identify areas for deeper study', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Etiquette in Modern Technology', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Apply Islamic etiquette principles to modern technology use: social media, video content, games, and apps — asking "is this beneficial? Does it bring me closer or farther from Allah?"', 'instructions' => '1. The principle: every permissible thing is judged by its use. Technology is a tool.\n2. Apply to 5 digital activities: WhatsApp, YouTube, games, TikTok, online learning.\n3. Islamic criteria: does it waste time (lahw)? Does it lead to haram? Does it benefit deen or dunya?\n4. Write your personal "Digital Adab" charter.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Evaluate 5 digital activities using Islamic criteria and write a personal digital adab charter', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Building a Relationship with Allah: Khushu in Prayer', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the concept of khushu (deep presence and focus) in salah, why it is essential, and 5 practical techniques to build it — transforming prayer from routine to a real meeting with Allah.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain khushu: "Recite (the Quran) in measured recitation... standing, sitting, and lying down." True salah is a meeting with Allah.\n2. Why does the mind wander? Identify your 3 most common distractions.\n3. 5 techniques: understand what you recite, pray as if it is your last prayer, visualise standing before Allah, slow down, short surah with understanding.\n4. Implement one technique in your next prayer and report back.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply at least one khushu technique in a real prayer and reflect on the difference', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Understanding Fitrah: The Natural Inclination', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the concept of fitrah — the natural disposition Allah placed in every human to recognise truth — and how Islam nurtures while other influences can cloud it.', 'instructions' => '1. Hadith: "Every child is born on fitrah — their parents make them a Jew, Christian, or Magian." (Bukhari)\n2. Fitrah practices: 5 acts of fitrah (circumcision, shaving the pubic hair, clipping nails, removing underarm hair, trimming the moustache).\n3. Fitrah as inner compass: all humans recognise basic justice, compassion, and truth — Islam refines this.\n4. Discussion: has there been a moment where you felt something was wrong before you knew the ruling? That is fitrah.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the concept of fitrah, list its 5 practices, and connect it to moral intuition', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Al-Wala wal-Bara: Loyalty and Avoidance in Context', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 10, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the nuanced concept of al-wala wal-bara — loving for the sake of Allah and avoiding for His sake — ensuring a balanced understanding that avoids extremism and isolationism.', 'instructions' => '1. Define al-wala wal-bara in its proper scholarly context.\n2. What is required: love for fellow believers, following and supporting Islamic community.\n3. What it does NOT mean: hating non-Muslims as people, refusing to live alongside them, being unjust to them. Islam commands adl (justice) to all.\n4. Discuss: how do you maintain Islamic identity AND be a good neighbour, citizen, friend?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain al-wala wal-bara correctly, distinguishing its valid meaning from misapplication', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],


            // Islamic Studies 46-50
            ['title' => 'Tazkiyah: Purifying the Soul', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Understand tazkiyah (purification of the soul) as a Quranic goal, identify destructive spiritual diseases (kibr, hasad, riya, bukhl) and their cures.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: tazkiyah is the process of cleaning the heart.\n2. The 4 destructive diseases: kibr (arrogance), hasad (envy), riya (showing off), bukhl (miserliness).\n3. For each: Quranic or hadith evidence + its cure.\n4. Reflect: which of these 4 is the greatest struggle for you personally?\n5. Commit to a 1-week cure practice.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify 4 spiritual diseases, cite their evidence, and commit to one cure practice', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Understanding Qadar: Divine Decree', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the 4 components of belief in qadar (divine decree) and understand how it coexists with human free will and personal responsibility.', 'instructions' => '1. 4 components: ilm (Allah\'s knowledge), kitabah (written decree), mashee\'ah (Allah\'s will), khalq (creation of all things).\n2. Does believing in qadar mean we don\'t need to try? No — explain with the famous hadith: "Tie your camel, then put your trust in Allah."\n3. How does qadar bring peace in times of loss?\n4. Write about a difficulty in your life — how does qadar help you understand it?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the 4 components of qadar and reconcile it with human responsibility using hadith', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Seerah: The Final Sermon and Farewell Hajj', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the Prophet\'s ﷺ Final Sermon at Arafah — its contents on human equality, rights of women, prohibition of riba, brotherhood — and the revelation of the completion of Islam.', 'instructions' => '1. Context: Hajjat al-Wada (Farewell Hajj) — 100,000+ people present.\n2. Read key passages of the Final Sermon.\n3. Key messages: equality of all humans, rights of women, sanctity of life and wealth, brotherhood in Islam.\n4. "Today I have perfected your religion for you." (5:3) — what does completion of the religion mean?\n5. This was said 63 days before the Prophet ﷺ passed.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, sermon text', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify the main messages of the Final Sermon and connect them to Quranic completion', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'The Prophet\'s ﷺ Final Days and the Passing', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Study the last days of the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ — his illness, final advice to the ummah, Abu Bakr\'s famous words in the masjid — building love and connection to his memory.', 'instructions' => '1. The final days: illness began after returning from farewell Hajj.\n2. Despite fever: led prayer as long as possible, then appointed Abu Bakr to lead.\n3. Final words included: taking care of prayer, women, and the right hand (slaves).\n4. Abu Bakr\'s famous response: "Whoever worshipped Muhammad, Muhammad is dead. But whoever worshipped Allah — Allah is Alive and never dies."\n5. Write: what do you feel when you hear this story?', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, reference text', 'learning_objectives' => 'Narrate the events of the Prophet\'s final days and reflect on Abu Bakr\'s statement of tawheed', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'My Islamic Learning Plan', 'subject' => 'islamic_studies', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Design a comprehensive personal Islamic learning plan: daily Quran, weekly seerah reading, Islamic Studies topics to master, and a 6-month milestone goal.', 'instructions' => '1. Review: what have I learned this term? (Aqeedah, fiqh, seerah, akhlaq, Quran)\n2. What do I still want to know?\n3. Create a 6-month plan: daily (Quran), weekly (one seerah reading), monthly (one fiqh topic).\n4. Choose one Islamic book or resource to read this month.\n5. Write an intention statement: "I seek knowledge for the sake of Allah, so that..."\n6. Identify one Islamic teacher or mentor you want to learn from.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, learning plan template', 'learning_objectives' => 'Produce a structured 6-month personal Islamic learning plan with daily, weekly, and monthly components', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],

            // Arabic 1-15
            ['title' => 'Arabic Alphabet: All 28 Letters', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn all 28 letters of the Arabic alphabet — recognise, name, and pronounce each letter in isolation, understanding the spiritual importance of learning the language of the Quran.', 'instructions' => '1. Introduction: Arabic is the language of the Quran — learning it is a special act of worship.\n2. Learn and practise all 28 letters in order: Alif to Ya.\n3. Alphabet song or chart — drill complete sequence.\n4. Identify which letters look similar (Ba, Ta, Tha; Jim, Ha, Kha, etc.).\n5. Write the full alphabet from memory.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic alphabet chart, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Write and name all 28 Arabic letters in alphabetical order from memory', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Short Vowels: Fathah, Kasrah, Dhammah', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the three short vowels (harakat) — fathah, kasrah, dhammah — and practise reading Arabic letters with each vowel applied.', 'instructions' => '1. Introduce fathah (a sound), kasrah (i sound), dhammah (u sound).\n2. Read each: Ba, Bi, Bu / Ta, Ti, Tu / through the alphabet.\n3. Practise on 5 simple Arabic words with vowels marked.\n4. Write 5 letters with each vowel.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic vowels worksheet, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read Arabic consonants with all three short vowels applied correctly', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Numbers 1–20', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn Arabic/Hindu-Arabic numerals 1–20 in both spoken and written form, understanding that Arabic numerals are the origin of all modern number systems.', 'instructions' => '1. Introduce Arabic numerals 1–10 visually.\n2. Count and match: ١ ٢ ٣ ٤ ٥ ٦ ٧ ٨ ٩ ١٠ — what is interesting about 4, 5, 6, and 7?\n3. Numbers 11–20: the pattern.\n4. Dictation: say the number in English, child writes the Arabic numeral.\n5. Connect: we use these every day — all "Western" numerals come from the Arab-Islamic world.', 'materials_needed' => 'Numbers card set, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read and write Arabic numerals 1–20 and explain their historical origin', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Basic Arabic Greetings and Everyday Phrases', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn 15 essential Arabic greetings and everyday phrases used by Muslims worldwide, understanding their meanings and when to use them.', 'instructions' => '1. As-Salamu Alaykum — its meaning and the reply.\n2. Bismillah, Alhamdulillah, Insha\'Allah, Mashaa\'Allah, Subhanallah, JazakAllahu Khairan, Barakallahu Feek, Inna Lillahi, A\'udhu Billah.\n3. For each: Arabic pronunciation, meaning, and situation.\n4. Role-play a 2-minute conversation using at least 5 phrases.\n5. Discuss: these phrases connect every Muslim around the world.', 'materials_needed' => 'Phrase card set, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Use 15 Islamic phrases correctly in context', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Reading Arabic: Two-Letter Combinations', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 9, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Practise reading two-letter combinations (consonant + vowel) rapidly — building the foundation for reading Quranic Arabic.', 'instructions' => '1. Review: letters + fathah, kasrah, dhammah.\n2. Read rapid two-letter combos: Ba + fathah = Ba; Ba + kasrah = Bi; Ba + dhammah = Bu.\n3. Flash card drill: 30 two-letter combinations read as fast as possible.\n4. Write 5 two-letter combinations from dictation.\n5. Find examples in a Quranic verse.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flash cards, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read 30 two-letter Arabic combinations accurately and fluently', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Sukoon and Tanween: Reading Arabic Accurately', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn sukoon (absence of vowel) and tanween (doubled vowels — an, in, un) and practise reading Arabic words using these marks correctly.', 'instructions' => '1. Sukoon: a small circle above the letter — means no vowel, close the syllable.\n2. Tanween: double fathah (an), double kasrah (in), double dhammah (un) — seen mostly at word endings.\n3. Practise: read 10 words with sukoon, 10 with tanween.\n4. Find examples of tanween in Al-Fatiha.\n5. Write 5 words from dictation with sukoon correctly placed.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic reading worksheet, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read Arabic words with sukoon and tanween marks accurately', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Letter Forms: Beginning, Middle, End, Alone', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn that Arabic letters change shape depending on their position in a word (beginning, middle, end, isolated) and practise recognising all position forms for 10 key letters.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: Arabic letters are connected within words, and most letters change form by position.\n2. For each of 10 letters (Ba, Ta, Jim, Ra, Sin, Ain, Fa, Qaf, Kaf, Lam): draw all 4 forms.\n3. Spot the letter: circle a specific letter in a Quranic passage.\n4. Connect 5 letters into a short word and identify the form of each.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic letter forms chart, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify all 4 positional forms of 10 key Arabic letters in connected text', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Vocabulary: The Body, Colours, Family', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => true, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn 30 essential Arabic words across three categories: body parts, colours, and family members — with pronunciation, written form, and usage.', 'instructions' => '1. Category 1 (Body): head, hand, foot, eye, nose, mouth, heart (10 words).\n2. Category 2 (Colours): red, blue, green, white, black, yellow, brown (7 words).\n3. Category 3 (Family): father, mother, brother, sister, grandfather, grandmother, son, daughter, uncle, aunt (10 words).\n4. Flash card drill all 30.\n5. Write a 3-sentence Arabic "about my family" using known words.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flash cards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Recall and write 30 Arabic vocabulary words across 3 categories', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Reading: Three-Letter Words', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Build reading fluency with three-letter Arabic words — reading them with full vowel marks accurately, connecting to root-based Arabic vocabulary.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: most Arabic words come from 3-letter roots (roots).\n2. Practise 20 three-letter words with full vowels: Kitaab (book), Bayt (house), Walad (boy), Bint (girl), etc.\n3. Read aloud: parent or teacher checks pronunciation.\n4. Write 10 from dictation.\n5. Match Arabic word to English meaning — no word list allowed.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic word cards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read and write 20 three-letter Arabic words with full vowel marks accurately', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Sentence Structure: Subject + Predicate', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn basic Arabic sentence structure: the nominal sentence (mubtada + khabar) and verbal sentence (fi\'l + fa\'il) and construct simple sentences.', 'instructions' => '1. Nominal sentence: subject (mubtada) + predicate (khabar): "Al-waladu kabeir" (the boy is big).\n2. Verbal sentence: verb (fi\'l) + subject (fa\'il): "Rakaba al-waladu" (the boy rode).\n3. Build 5 nominal sentences using known vocabulary.\n4. Build 5 verbal sentences.\n5. Translate 5 simple English sentences into Arabic structure.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, vocabulary list', 'learning_objectives' => 'Construct 5 nominal and 5 verbal Arabic sentences using correct structure', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Root System: Understanding Word Families', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore the Arabic root system — how a 3-letter root generates dozens of related words — using the root K-T-B (write) as a model, then exploring 2 more roots.', 'instructions' => '1. Explain: Arabic is root-based — 3 consonants form a root, patterns create different words.\n2. K-T-B: Kataba (he wrote), Kitaab (book), Kaatib (writer), Maktaba (library), Maktub (written/letter).\n3. Explore root \'I-L-M: Alima (he knew), Ilm (knowledge), Alim (scholar), Ma\'loom (known).\n4. What does this reveal about how Arabic captures connected ideas?\n5. Find one more root and list 4 words from it.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, Arabic dictionary', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain the Arabic root system and generate 4+ words from 3 different roots', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Reading Quranic Arabic: Surah Al-Fatiha Word by Word', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Analyse Al-Fatiha word by word in Arabic — the root of each word, its grammatical role, and its meaning — building deep connection to the most recited Quranic passage.', 'instructions' => '1. Al-hamd: root h-m-d (praise) — all praise.\n2. Lillahi: li = for, Allah = Allah.\n3. Continue through all 7 verses word by word.\n4. After completing the analysis: recite Al-Fatiha in salah for the next 3 days focusing on the meaning of each word.\n5. Write: what is different about salah when you understand every word?', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, Arabic reference, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Analyse every word of Al-Fatiha in Arabic with root, meaning, and grammatical role', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Conversation: Daily Routine', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Hold a simple Arabic conversation about daily routine using time expressions, verbs, and common phrases, combining vocabulary from previous lessons.', 'instructions' => '1. Vocabulary review: daily routine verbs (woke up, prayed, ate, went, studied, slept).\n2. Time expressions: in the morning, at noon, in the evening, at night.\n3. Model conversation: A and B describe their morning in Arabic.\n4. Role-play with family — keep it to 8 exchanges.\n5. Write out your own daily routine in 5 Arabic sentences.', 'materials_needed' => 'Vocabulary list, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Participate in a simple 8-exchange Arabic conversation about daily routine', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Writing: Joining Letters into Words', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 6, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Practise joining Arabic letters to form words — reinforcing letter forms (beginning, middle, end) and the 6 non-joining letters.', 'instructions' => '1. Review the 6 non-joining letters: Alif, Da, Dha, Ra, Za, Waw — they only connect to letters on their right.\n2. Practise joining 5 CVC words: Kitab (k-i-t-a-b), Bayt (b-a-y-t).\n3. Write 5 words from dictation, focusing on correct letter connections.\n4. Spot the non-joining letter in each word.\n5. Write your name in Arabic.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic writing worksheet, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Join Arabic letters into words correctly, identifying non-joining letters', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Vocabulary: Nature, Animals, Food', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn 30 Arabic words across nature, animals, and food — building broad vocabulary for conversation and Quranic comprehension.', 'instructions' => '1. Nature (10): sun, moon, star, sky, sea, river, mountain, tree, rain, wind.\n2. Animals (10): lion, elephant, bird, fish, horse, camel, cat, dog, butterfly, bee.\n3. Food (10): bread, water, milk, dates, honey, fruit, meat, rice, egg, soup.\n4. Flash card drill all 30.\n5. Write a 3-sentence Arabic story using 6 of these words.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flash cards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Recall 30 Arabic vocabulary words across nature, animals, and food categories', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],


            // Arabic 16-40
            ['title' => 'Arabic Grammar: Masculine and Feminine Nouns', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn how Arabic distinguishes masculine and feminine nouns — mostly through the ta marbuta (ة) ending — and practise applying gender agreement in simple phrases.', 'instructions' => '1. In Arabic every noun is either masculine or feminine — there is no neutral.\n2. Rule: most feminine nouns end in ta marbuta (ة): Muallim (teacher, m.) vs. Muallima (teacher, f.).\n3. Exceptions to memorise: sun, wind, fire, earth (feminine despite no ta marbuta).\n4. Practise: identify gender of 20 nouns.\n5. Form 5 noun + adjective phrases with gender agreement.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, noun list, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Identify masculine/feminine for 20 Arabic nouns and apply gender agreement in 5 phrases', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Plurals: Sound and Broken Plurals', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn how Arabic forms plurals — sound masculine plural (+oon/een), sound feminine plural (+aat), and broken plurals (internal vowel change) — the most distinctive feature of Arabic grammar.', 'instructions' => '1. Sound masculine plural: Muslimoon/Muslimeen (Muslims, m.)\n2. Sound feminine plural: Muslimaat (Muslims, f.)\n3. Broken plural: Kitaab → Kutub, Bayt → Buyoot, Rajul → Rijaal.\n4. Broken plurals have ~15 common patterns — introduce 5 most common.\n5. Practise making plural of 10 known nouns.\n6. Find broken plurals in Al-Fatiha or Al-Baqarah (first 5 verses).', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, noun list, Quran', 'learning_objectives' => 'Form sound plurals for 5 nouns and identify broken plural pattern for 5 nouns', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Verbs: Past Tense Conjugation', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn past tense verb conjugation in Arabic using the root K-T-B as a model — conjugating for he/she/they/I/we across the full paradigm.', 'instructions' => '1. Past tense root form: Kataba (he wrote) — the citation form (3rd person masculine singular past).\n2. Conjugate fully: Kataba (he), Katabat (she), Katabu (they m.), Katabna (they f.), Katabtu (I), Katabna (we).\n3. Now conjugate Dhahaba (he went) the same way.\n4. Find these forms in a Quranic passage.\n5. Write a past tense story using 5 different verbs.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, conjugation table, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Conjugate 2 Arabic verbs fully in past tense across all pronouns', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic in the Quran: Connecting Language and Revelation', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Explore why the Quran was revealed in Arabic, the concept of i\'jaz (miraculous inimitability) of the Quran, and how Arabic vocabulary deepens Quranic understanding.', 'instructions' => '1. "Indeed We have revealed it as an Arabic Quran that you might reason." (12:2)\n2. The Arabs of 7th century were masters of poetry and language — yet no one could match the Quran.\n3. I\'jaz: linguistic miracle — one of the proofs of the Quran\'s divine origin.\n4. Example: the word "Sabr" (patience/steadfastness) — deeper than any English equivalent.\n5. Choose one Quranic verse, look up the Arabic root of 3 words, and discover what the root reveals.', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, Arabic dictionary, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Explain i\'jaz and demonstrate deepened Quranic understanding from 3 Arabic root analyses', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Vocabulary: Mosque, Prayer, and Quranic Terms', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn 25 essential Arabic terms related to mosque, prayer, and the Quran — vocabulary that every Muslim child encounters daily in worship.', 'instructions' => '1. Mosque: Masjid, Minaret, Mihrab, Minbar, Imam, Wudu area, Carpet.\n2. Prayer: Salah, Rakat, Sujood, Ruku, Qiyam, Tashahhud, Tasleem.\n3. Quran: Surah, Ayah, Juz, Hizb, Tajweed, Hafidh, Maqra, Mushaf.\n4. Flash drill all 25.\n5. Describe a prayer in Arabic using 10 of these terms.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flash cards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Use 25 mosque/prayer/Quranic Arabic terms correctly in context', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Writing Practice: Dictation Passage', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Build Arabic writing confidence through structured dictation — hearing Arabic sentences read aloud and writing them from memory with correct letter joining.', 'instructions' => '1. Preparation: review all vocabulary from previous 3 Arabic lessons.\n2. Dictation: adult reads 5 simple sentences aloud in Arabic, child writes.\n3. Self-correct: compare to written original.\n4. Rewrite any sentences with errors 3 times.\n5. Read back each sentence aloud for pronunciation practice.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, answer key', 'learning_objectives' => 'Write 5 dictated Arabic sentences accurately from hearing with correct letter joining', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic: Days of the Week and Months', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the 7 days of the week and 12 months in Arabic — both the modern Arabic names and the Islamic (Hijri) month names — connecting Muslim time to the Arabic language.', 'instructions' => '1. Days: Ahad (Sun), Ithnayn (Mon), Thulatha (Tue), Arba\'a (Wed), Khamees (Thu), Jumu\'ah (Fri), Sabt (Sat).\n2. Special note on Jumu\'ah — day of gathering, its Quranic surah.\n3. Gregorian months in Arabic (Yanayir, Febrayr, etc.).\n4. Hijri months: Muharram, Safar, through to Dhul-Hijjah — with significance notes.\n5. What is today in both calendars?', 'materials_needed' => 'Calendar, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Name all 7 days and 12 Hijri months in Arabic with their significance', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Comprehension: A Short Story', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Read a short Arabic story (fully vowelled, 5–8 sentences) independently, then answer comprehension questions in Arabic — building reading and comprehension fluency together.', 'instructions' => '1. Read the Arabic story (fully vowelled) once silently, once aloud.\n2. Answer 5 comprehension questions in Arabic (Who? What? Where? When? Why?).\n3. Identify 3 vocabulary words you didn\'t know — look them up.\n4. Retell the story aloud in Arabic using your own words.\n5. Write an alternate ending in 2 Arabic sentences.', 'materials_needed' => 'Arabic story reader, dictionary, pencil', 'learning_objectives' => 'Read and comprehend a 5–8 sentence Arabic story, answer 5 questions, and retell orally', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic: Prepositions and Location Words', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn essential Arabic prepositions (in, on, under, between, with, for, from, to) and location/direction words — and use them in describing a scene.', 'instructions' => '1. Prepositions: Fi (in), Ala (on), Tahta (under), Bayna (between), Ma\'a (with), Li (for), Min (from), Ila (to).\n2. Note: prepositions in Arabic trigger kasrah (genitive case) on the following noun.\n3. Describe a room using 6 prepositions in Arabic sentences.\n4. Translate 5 English sentences with prepositions into Arabic.\n5. Find 3 prepositions in the first 5 verses of the Quran.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, Quran', 'learning_objectives' => 'Use 8 Arabic prepositions correctly to describe location, and identify 3 in Quranic text', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Present Tense Verbs in Arabic', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn present tense (mudhari\') conjugation in Arabic — how verbs transform for different subjects — focusing on 2 common movement/action verbs.', 'instructions' => '1. Mudhari\' (present/future): Yaktub (he writes), Taktub (she writes), Aktub (I write), Naktub (we write).\n2. The mudhari\' prefix pattern: Ya/Ta/A/Na.\n3. Conjugate Yadhhab (he goes) fully.\n4. Find mudhari\' verbs in the first 10 verses of Al-Baqarah — count them.\n5. Write a present-tense paragraph about daily Islamic activities.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, conjugation chart, Quran', 'learning_objectives' => 'Conjugate 2 Arabic verbs in present tense and identify mudhari\' forms in Quranic text', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Adjectives: Agreement and Description', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn how Arabic adjectives must agree with nouns in gender and number — and build descriptive noun phrases using 15 common adjectives.', 'instructions' => '1. Adjective agreement rule: adjective follows noun and matches in gender, number, and definiteness.\n2. Kabeer (big m.) / Kabeera (big f.) / Kibaar (big pl.).\n3. Learn 15 adjectives: big, small, good, bad, beautiful, ugly, near, far, new, old, strong, weak, happy, sad, fast.\n4. Build 10 noun + adjective phrases — 5 masculine, 5 feminine.\n5. Describe a person in 5 adjective-rich Arabic sentences.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flashcards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Apply adjective agreement rules to construct 10 Arabic noun+adjective phrases correctly', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic: Asking and Answering Questions', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn Arabic question words and how to form and answer simple questions — building essential conversational Arabic ability.', 'instructions' => '1. Question words: Man (who?), Ma/Matha (what?), Ayna (where?), Mata (when?), Kayfa (how?), Limadha (why?), Kam (how many?).\n2. Yes/No questions: use Hal + sentence.\n3. Model Q&A conversations using all 7 question types.\n4. Interview a family member in Arabic — 7 questions.\n5. Write 7 questions about your school day in Arabic.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Form and answer questions using all 7 Arabic question words in 7-question conversational exchange', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Reading: Ayat al-Kursi Word by Word', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 9, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 35, 'difficulty' => 'hard', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Deeply analyse Ayat al-Kursi (Al-Baqarah 2:255) word by word in Arabic — the most important single verse in the Quran — building both linguistic understanding and spiritual connection.', 'instructions' => '1. Read Ayat al-Kursi aloud from memory (check ability/fluency).\n2. Go word by word: Allah, La ilaha illa Huwa, Al-Hayy, Al-Qayyum — what does each mean and why is this order significant?\n3. The 10 divine attributes mentioned in this verse — list and define each.\n4. Grammar: find at least 3 definite nouns (with Al-) and explain the effect.\n5. Reflect: why did the Prophet ﷺ call this the greatest verse?', 'materials_needed' => 'Quran, Arabic dictionary, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Analyse every word of Ayat al-Kursi in Arabic and identify all 10 divine attributes', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Islamic Supplications (Du\'as) Word by Word', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Analyse 5 essential daily du\'as word by word in Arabic — morning, evening, before meals, before sleep, and after adhan — transforming rote memorisation into conscious supplication.', 'instructions' => '1. Morning dua (Asbahna wa asbahal mulku lillah).\n2. Evening dua (Amsayna wa amsal mulku lillah).\n3. Before eating (Bismillah — what does adding Bismillah before food actually mean in Arabic?).\n4. Before sleep (Bismika Allahumma amootu wa ahya).\n5. After adhan (Allahumma Rabba hadhihid-da\'watit-tammah).\n6. For each: word-by-word breakdown, then recite it once with understanding.', 'materials_needed' => 'Du\'a book or reference, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Translate 5 daily du\'as word by word from Arabic and recite each with understanding', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Calligraphy: Writing Bismillah', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn the art of Arabic Naskh calligraphy by carefully writing Bismillah ar-Rahman ar-Raheem — understanding both the spiritual meaning and the aesthetic tradition of Islamic calligraphy.', 'instructions' => '1. Introduce Islamic calligraphy as an art form — one of the highest forms of Islamic art.\n2. The 6 classical scripts — Naskh is the most common for printing and learning.\n3. Practise writing Bismillah in clear Naskh: slow, deliberate strokes.\n4. Learn the meaning: In the name of Allah, the Most Gracious, the Most Merciful.\n5. Make a final careful calligraphy piece of Bismillah to hang at home.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil or calligraphy pen, good paper, Bismillah guide sheet', 'learning_objectives' => 'Write Bismillah in clear Arabic Naskh script and explain the meaning of each word', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic Vocabulary: Emotions and Character Traits', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn 20 Arabic words for emotions and character traits — connecting language learning to Islamic character development and self-expression.', 'instructions' => '1. Emotions (10): happy (sa\'eed), sad (hazeen), angry (ghadban), afraid (kha\'if), surprised (mutajaarib), grateful (shaakir), hopeful (mut\'ammil), patient (saboor), content (qani\'), worried (qaalib).\n2. Character traits (10): honest (sadiq), brave (shaja\'), kind (lateef), generous (kareem), humble (mutawadhi\'), trustworthy (ameen), merciful (raheem), wise (hakeem), just (aadil), strong (qawi).\n3. Flash drill.\n4. Which 3 character traits do you most want to develop? Write 3 Arabic sentences about why.', 'materials_needed' => 'Flash cards, pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Recall and use 20 Arabic emotion and character trait words in written sentences', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic: Talking About What I Like and Dislike', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 10, 'duration_minutes' => 20, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Learn to express preferences in Arabic using Uhibbu (I love), La uhibbu (I don\'t love), Ufadhdhil (I prefer) and apply them in a structured self-introduction conversation.', 'instructions' => '1. Uhibbu (I love/like): Uhibbu al-qiraa (I love reading).\n2. La uhibbu (I don\'t like): La uhibbu al-kasal (I don\'t like laziness).\n3. Ufadhdhil (I prefer): Ufadhdhil al-Quran \'ala at-television (I prefer the Quran to TV).\n4. Build 10 sentences using these 3 structures.\n5. Self-introduction speech: 5 things I like, 2 I dislike, 1 I prefer — all in Arabic.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook', 'learning_objectives' => 'Produce 10 Arabic sentences expressing preference using 3 sentence structures', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Arabic: Describing My Environment', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 8, 'age_max' => 11, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Describe your home, classroom, and neighbourhood in Arabic — combining nouns, adjectives, prepositions, and verbs into flowing descriptive paragraphs.', 'instructions' => '1. Review: prepositions, adjectives, vocabulary (rooms of a house, classroom objects).\n2. Describe your bedroom in Arabic: 5 object-location sentences.\n3. Describe your classroom: 5 sentences.\n4. Describe your neighbourhood or masjid: 5 sentences.\n5. Read all 3 paragraphs aloud for pronunciation practice.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, vocabulary lists', 'learning_objectives' => 'Produce three 5-sentence Arabic descriptive paragraphs about home, classroom, and neighbourhood', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'Reviewing Arabic: What I Know Now', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 30, 'difficulty' => 'medium', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Comprehensive Arabic review activity — testing alphabet, vocabulary, grammar, reading, and conversation skills across all topics covered, with a personal Arabic learning reflection.', 'instructions' => '1. Section A — Alphabet: write full alphabet from memory.\n2. Section B — Vocabulary: translate 20 words (mix of all vocabulary categories).\n3. Section C — Grammar: form 5 sentences using 5 different grammar structures.\n4. Section D — Reading: read a 5-sentence passage and answer 3 comprehension questions.\n5. Section E — Reflection: what have I learned in Arabic? What surprised me? What do I still want to learn?\n6. Make a personal Arabic dictionary with all vocabulary learned so far.', 'materials_needed' => 'Pencil, notebook, review worksheet', 'learning_objectives' => 'Demonstrate mastery across alphabet, vocabulary, grammar, and reading with a personal reflection', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],
            ['title' => 'My Arabic Learning Journey: Next Steps', 'subject' => 'arabic', 'age_min' => 7, 'age_max' => 12, 'duration_minutes' => 25, 'difficulty' => 'easy', 'is_free' => false, 'thumbnail_url' => null, 'description' => 'Celebrate and consolidate Arabic learning progress — creating a personal Arabic portfolio, setting goals for the next level, and understanding the journey from beginner to Quranic comprehension.', 'instructions' => '1. Review: what can I now do in Arabic that I couldn\'t do before?\n2. Create an Arabic portfolio: best work, vocabulary list, favourite du\'a, favourite verse analysis.\n3. The journey to Quranic comprehension: typical milestones from beginner to reading the Quran with understanding.\n4. Choose 3 goals for the next 3 months in Arabic.\n5. Write an Istia\'itha and Bismillah from memory and reflect on what it means.', 'materials_needed' => 'Portfolio folder, pencil, all previous Arabic work', 'learning_objectives' => 'Assemble a personal Arabic portfolio and set 3 concrete goals for continued Arabic learning', 'age_group' => 'school', 'is_muslim_only' => true],

